<h2>Crowdfunding Experiment - Project Creator</h2>  
<br>

<p>In this study, you will play the role of a Project Creator on a crowdfunding site. Crowdfunding sites are websites where people can post projects and ask for small donations from a large number of people over the Internet.</p>

<p>In this simulation, you will be able to post projects to a simulated crowdfunding site where <strong><%= NUMBER_OF_DONORS_PER_GROUP %></strong> donors can decide to donate to your project. Each donor has <strong><%= AMOUNT_DONOR_CAN_DONATE_PER_ROUND %></strong> credits that he or she can choose to donate. Donors can donate all credits, some or no credits.</p>
                                                                                                                            
<p>You are given a budget of <strong><%= AMOUNT_CREATOR_CAN_SPEND_PER_ROUND %></strong> credits. To post a project to the site costs <strong><%= COST_TO_CREATE_PROJECT %></strong> credits. You can post as many projects as you have a budget for.</p>

<p>If you choose to post a project, there are two choices you must make about what type of project to post. The first choice is the risk level. You can create a high risk project which requires <strong><%= CREATOR_EARNINGS_HIGH_VALUE_PROJECT %></strong> credits in donations, or a low risk project which requires <strong><%= CREATOR_EARNINGS_LOW_VALUE_PROJECT %></strong> credits in donations. If a high risk project is completed, you earn <strong><%= CREATOR_EARNINGS_HIGH_VALUE_PROJECT %></strong> credits. If a low risk project is completed, you earn <strong><%= CREATOR_EARNINGS_LOW_VALUE_PROJECT %></strong> credits.</p>

<p>The second choice you make is the popularity of the project. You can create popular projects or niche projects. To incentivize donations to your projects, donors earn a payoff when a project is completed. If you choose to create a popular project, all donors earn the same payoff if the project is completed, and this payoff is moderately sized. If you create a niche project, two donors will earn a very high payoff if the project is completed, and two other donors will earn only a small payoff. The table below describes these payoffs in more detail:</p>   

